.IX Title ""<STANDARD INPUT>" 1"
.TH "<STANDARD INPUT>" 1 "LRmapqtl" "QTL Cartographer v1.17" "User Contributed Perl Documentation"
.SH "NAME"
LRmapqtl \- Single marker QTL analysis.
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
\&\fBLRmapqtl\fR [ \fB\-o\fR \fIoutput\fR ] [ \fB\-i\fR \fIinput\fR ] [ \fB\-m\fR \fImapfile\fR ]
[ \fB\-r\fR \fIreps\fR ] [ \fB\-t\fR \fItrait\fR ]
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
\&\fBLRmapqtl\fR uses simple linear regression to map quantitative trait loci to
a map of molecular markers. It requires a molecular map that could be a random one produced by 
\&\fBRmap\fR,  or a real one in the same format as the output of 
\&\fBRmap\fR.   The sample could be a randomly generated one from 
\&\fBRcross\fR or a real one in the same format as the output of 
\&\fBRcross\fR.
.SH "OPTIONS"
.IX Header "OPTIONS"
See \fB\f(BIQTLcart\fB\|(1)\fR for more information on the global options
\&\fB\-h\fR for help, \fB\-A\fR for automatic,  \fB\-V\fR for non-Verbose
\&\fB\-W path\fR for a working directory, \fB\-R file\fR to specify a resource
file, \fB\-e\fR to specify the log file, \fB\-s\fR to specify a seed for the
random number generator and \fB\-X stem\fR to specify a filename stem. 
The options below are specific to this program.
.PP
If you use this program without specifying any options, then you will
get into a menu that allows you to set them interactively.   
.IP "\fB\-o\fR" 4
.IX Item "-o"
This requires a filename for output.   \fBLRmapqtl\fR will append the file if
it exists, and create a new file if it does not.   If not used, then \fBLRmapqtl\fR will use
\&\fIqtlcart.lr\fR.  
.IP "\fB\-i\fR" 4
.IX Item "-i"
This requires an input filename.    This file must exist.  It should be in the
same format as the output of \fBRcross\fR. The default file is \fIqtlcart.cro\fR. 
.IP "\fB\-m\fR" 4
.IX Item "-m"
\&\fBLRmapqtl\fR requires a genetic linkage map.  This option requires
the name of a file containing the map.  It should be in the same format
that \fBRmap\fR outputs.  The default file is \fIqtlcart.map\fR. 
.IP "\fB\-r\fR" 4
.IX Item "-r"
\&\fBLRmapqtl\fR will do a permutation test  \fIa la\fR
Churchill and Doerge (1994).  This option specifies the number of permutions to
do.  It is zero by default, which means no permuation test is done.  If used, you must specify 
a positive integer.  Usually, 1,000 is sufficient.
.IP "\fB\-t\fR" 4
.IX Item "-t"
Use this to specify which trait \fBLRmapqtl\fR
will analyze.  If this number is greater than
the number of traits, then all traits will be analyzed.   The default is
to analyze trait 1 only.
.SH "MODEL"
.IX Header "MODEL"
The basic linear model is 
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        Trait = Mean + Slope x Marker + Error
.Ve
.PP
The marker value will be in the range [\-1, 1] inclusive.   Two hypotheses are
compared.  The null hypothesis is that the Slope is zero.  The alternate is that
the Slope is non\-zero.  A p\-value for the likelihood ratio of these to 
hypotheses is calculated for each marker-trait combination.   \fBLRmapqtl\fR
outputs a table with parameter estimates, F statistics, Likelihood ratios and
p\-values.   
.SH "INPUT FORMAT"
.IX Header "INPUT FORMAT"
The input format of the molecular map should be the same as that of the output 
format from the program 
\&\fBRmap\fR.   The input format of the individual data should be the same as the output format
of the program 
\&\fBRcross\fR.
.SH "EXAMPLES"
.IX Header "EXAMPLES"
.Vb 1
\&        % LRmapqtl -i corn.cro -m corn.map
.Ve
.PP
Calculates the regression coefficients for each marker on the dataset in \fIcorn.cro\fR 
using the genetic linkage map in \fIcorn.map\fR.
.SH "REFERENCES"
.IX Header "REFERENCES"
.IP "1." 4
Churchill, G. A.  and R. W. Doerge (1994) Empirical threshold values for 
quantitative trait mapping.
\&\fIGenetics\fR \fB138\fR, 963\-971.
